    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-21T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-21T21:00:00-05:00" n="117"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d117">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.102S/1974: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lockhart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-22T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 22, 1939—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 22—1:43 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1132. Chungking’s 626, December 4, 5 p.m., to the Department and the Department’s
                    231, December 7, 7 p.m., to Chungking. Chao Weitsu was unconditionally released
                    yesterday afternoon.</p>
                <p>A copy of the note quoted in Chungking’s 626, December 9 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >4</hi>], 5 p.m., was transmitted to the Chairman of the Shanghai Municipal
                    Council in accordance with the Department’s 231, December 7, 7 p.m.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Chungking.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lockhart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
